TY  - JOUR
T1  - Status, Intertemporal Choice, and Risk-Taking
AU  - Ray, Debraj
AU  - Robson, Arthur
Y1  - 2012/07/01
PY  - 2012
DA  - 2012/07/01
DO  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA9042
T2  - Econometrica
JF  - Econometrica
JO  - Econometrica
SP  - 1505
EP  - 1531
VL  - 80
IS  - 4
KW  - Status
KW  - growth
KW  - attitudes to risk
PB  - John Wiley & Sons, Ltd
SN  - 0012-9682
UR  - https://doi.org/10.3982/ECTA9042
Y2  - 2024/03/26
N2  - This paper studies endogenous risk-taking by embedding a concern for status (relative consumption) into an otherwise conventional model of economic growth. We prove that if the intertemporal production function is strictly concave, an equilibrium must converge to a unique steady state in which there is recurrent endogenous risk-taking. (The role played by concavity is clarified by considering a special case in which the production function is instead convex, in which there is no persistent risk-taking.) The steady state is fully characterized. It displays features that are consistent with the stylized facts that individuals both insure downside risk and gamble over upside risk, and it generates similar patterns of risk-taking and avoidance across environments with quite different overall wealth levels. Endogenous risk-taking here is generally Pareto-inefficient. A concern for status thus implies that persistent and inefficient risk-taking hinders the attainment of full equality.
ER  - 

